1. Introduction and Business Understanding¶

Introduction¶

In this lab, we will use different machine learning algorithms to implement clustering as a feature selection technique. We will compare a few of our existing models from Lab 2 to see if clustering provides any advantage on those models.

For the the regression models that predicted player wages, we make an assumption that the super star players, average players, new players, or other types of players can make a big influence on the players' wage. Therefore, there maybe outliers that may affect the accuracy of the regression models. A superstar player usually get extremely high wages and we believe the key feature to identify those players are the attacking skill features. We will implement clustering to find the potential groups from the attacking features. Then, we will use the clustered result combining with rest of the features to run regression tests.

We will be using MAE for the comparison. MAE measures the average magnitude of the errors in a set of predictions without considering their direction. It takes the average over the test sample of the absolute differences between prediction and actual observation where all individual differences have equal weight.
We carry over the Business Understanding and Data Preparation from Lab 2. More information related to Visualization and Data Preprocessing can be found in Lab 2.

Business Understanding¶

Kaggle dataset (https://www.kaggle.com/stefanoleone992/fifa-20-complete-player-dataset) players_20.csv is used in this lab. The dataset provides detailed information of all the soccer players statistics in various clubs of major soccer leagues in the world. The data is originally from the FIFA soccer game created by EA sports. This game estimates the abilities of the actual players and built the game according to the data. And the Kaggle dataset is scraped from www.sofifa.com, where the gaming data is collected. The data we used is last updated on Sept 19th 2019.

The dataset is important because the abilities of players is estimated from the actual players. FIFA is a very popular game and EA Sports is one of the largest sport video game developer. The player abilities estimate is quite accurate. Therefore, useful knowledge can be mined from the data for analyzing variety problems in the soccer industry. For example, wage analysis, player analysis, training strategy, budget analysis, sport gambling strategy plan can be performed using this dataset. Soccer has been a big industry which the market size is estimated to worth $488 billion in 2018 according to the Business Wire.

Due to the large number of features we have created a csv file that will serve as a metadata file as follows
1) File location: ../data/fifa20/data_desc.csv
2) The Name column as the exact name that is in our original dataset file and we will use this to load the file.
3) Description: The team has filled up the description of each feature describing it.
4) Variable_cat: We use this to categorise related features for example 'Position' indicates all the features related to various position attirbutes.
Using a metadata makes it easy in case we want to ignore certain attributes that are not relavant for our analysis by marking it as Ignore.

This image helps us understand various positions that a soccer players is assigned during a game. The feature player_positions represents multiple positions that a player can play in with a comma seperate value, the very first item in that list has a preferred field position of the player. The team_position is the current positon that the player is being used in the team. For our analysis we will use the players preferred positon.

The statistics of each individual player ability in respective positons are in seperate features on a scale of 1 to 100 as described in the table output aboive.

A goal keeper does not occupy any of the positions that a regular player occupies under normal circumstances which means he will not have any specific statistics for those features. A goal keeper on the other hand has a different set of features to capture his statistics, these are displayed in the table above in the Variable_cat field as 'GK'.

Refactor position features [Object to discrete]¶

The position features inculdes year over improvement / decrement. For example a player in st (Striker) position with a value of 89+2 is basically 89 with an increase (- would indicate decrease) of 2 from last year. Since we will not be doing any year over analysis, we will remove the suffix for these columns = ['ls','st','rs','lw','lf','cf','rf', 'rw','lam','cam','ram', 'lm','lcm','cm','rcm','rm','lwb','ldm', 'cdm','rdm', 'rwb','lb','lcb', 'cb','rcb','rb']

Dealing with missing values¶

The player positional features mentioned above and the skills features ['pace','shooting', 'passing','dribbling', 'defending','physic'] have a total of 2036 missing values. We see that all of them are categorized to play in the GK position (player_positions="GK", Goal Keeper). We will set these values to zero.

Goal Keeper specific attributes¶

The following features ['gk_diving','gk_handling','gk_kicking','gk_reflexes', 'gk_speed','gk_positioning'] are specific to goalkeepers. We see a total of 16242 mising values, which corrosponds to the non goalkeeper or regular positional players. We will set these values to zero. Also there are duplicate columns representing these same attributes which we will ignore ['goalkeeping_diving', 'goalkeeping_handling', 'goalkeeping_kicking', 'goalkeeping_positioning', 'goalkeeping_reflexes']

Average rating by age (Potential, Overall and Age)¶

In the plot below, we can see the gap between the potential of a player and his overall rating reduces as the player age increases. By the average age of 28, they merge and becomes the same. This makes sence as the potential of the younger players is higher. As the players age, they come closer to their overall rating.
We see a spike in the overall rating at age 41 due to the fact that there are only few players at that age. The few high ratings are pulling the average up.

4. Modeling and Evaluation 1: Train and adjust parameters¶

In the last two labs, we used supervised learning techniques to build machine learning models. The goal of clustering analysis is to find the natural grouping in data. We will do the clustering on scaled dataset from now on.

In the first step, we will consider regression analysis and compare it with clustering analysis.

Custom Scorers for Evaluating Regression Models¶

All regression models created in this notebook are validated using the following metrics:

  • Mean Absolute Error (MAE)

Common methods used for scoring

In [32]:
#Use mean absolute error (MAE) to score the regression models created 
#(the scale of MAE is identical to the response variable)
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, make_scorer, mean_squared_error, r2_score

#Function for Root mean squared error
#https://stackoverflow.com/questions/17197492/root-mean-square-error-in-python
def rmse(y_actual, y_predicted):
    return np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_actual, y_predicted))

#Function for Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) - Untested
#Adapted from - https://stackoverflow.com/questions/42250958/how-to-optimize-mape-code-in-python
def mape(y_actual, y_predicted): 
    mask = y_actual != 0
    return (np.fabs(y_actual - y_predicted)/y_actual)[mask].mean() * 100

#Create scorers for rmse and mape functions
mae_scorer = make_scorer(score_func=mean_absolute_error, greater_is_better=False)
rmse_scorer = make_scorer(score_func=rmse, greater_is_better=False)
mape_scorer = make_scorer(score_func=mape, greater_is_better=False)
r2_scorer = make_scorer(score_func=r2_score, greater_is_better=True)

#Make scorer array to pass into cross_validate() function for producing mutiple scores for each cv fold.
errorScoring = {'MAE':  mae_scorer, 
                'RMSE': rmse_scorer,
                'MAPE': mape_scorer,
                'R2': r2_scorer,
                }
In [33]:
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_validate
import seaborn as sns
# colors = ["windows blue", "amber", "greyish", "faded green", "dusty purple"]
# pal = sns.xkcd_palette(colors)
import pprint

def EvaluateRegressionEstimator(regEstimator, X, y, cv):
    
    scores = cross_validate(regEstimator, X, y, scoring=errorScoring, cv=cv, return_train_score=True)
    #print('scores = \n')
    #pp = pprint.PrettyPrinter(indent=1)
    #pp.pprint(scores)

    #cross val score sign-flips the outputs of MAE
    # https://github.com/scikit-learn/scikit-learn/issues/2439
    scores['test_MAE'] = scores['test_MAE'] * -1
    scores['test_MAPE'] = scores['test_MAPE'] * -1
    scores['test_RMSE'] = scores['test_RMSE'] * -1  

    #print mean MAE for all folds 
    maeAvg = scores['test_MAE'].mean()
    print_str = "The average MAE for all cv folds is: \t\t\t {maeAvg:.5}"
    print(print_str.format(maeAvg=maeAvg))

    #print mean test_MAPE for all folds
    scores['test_MAPE'] = scores['test_MAPE']
    mape_avg = scores['test_MAPE'].mean()
    print_str = "The average MAE percentage (MAPE) for all cv folds is: \t {mape_avg:.5}"
    print(print_str.format(mape_avg=mape_avg))

    #print mean MAE for all folds 
    RMSEavg = scores['test_RMSE'].mean()
    print_str = "The average RMSE for all cv folds is: \t\t\t {RMSEavg:.5}"
    print(print_str.format(RMSEavg=RMSEavg))
    
    #print mean R2 for all folds 
    R2avg = scores['test_R2'].mean()
    print_str = "The average R2 for all cv folds is: \t\t\t {R2avg:.5}"
    print(print_str.format(R2avg=R2avg))    
    print('*********************************************************')

    print('Cross Validation Fold Mean Error Scores')
    scoresResults = pd.DataFrame()
    scoresResults['MAE'] = scores['test_MAE']
    scoresResults['MAPE'] = scores['test_MAPE']
    scoresResults['RMSE'] = scores['test_RMSE']
    scoresResults['R2'] = scores['test_R2']
    print(scoresResults)
    return scoresResults

def plot_kde_y_yhat(y, y_):
    plot_df = pd.DataFrame()
    plot_df['y'] = y
    plot_df['yhat'] = y_
    
    # Change negative yhat to 0 as wage can't be negative value
    plot_df[plot_df['yhat']<0] = 0
    ax1 = sns.distplot(plot_df['y'], kde=True, color='#4472C4', hist=False, label='Actual wages')
    sns.distplot(plot_df['yhat'], kde=True, color='#FF9900', hist=False, label='Predicted wages', ax=ax1)
    ax1.set(xlim=(-10000,150000))
    ax1.set_title("Actual wages vs. Predicted wages")
    plt.xlabel('Wages ()')
    plt.ylabel('Gaussian Kernel Density Estimate')

evaluate_reg_model_performance methods uses a grid searchCV scikitlearn api to evaluate a set of models that are passed to it. The best performing model is identified with the graphs show comparative statistics. The evaluation is done as follows:
model_name: string representing the model name can be anything
params: List of model tuning paramters clf: the estimator classification to evaluate
X_train, y_train: The scaled train dataset, the grid search will use this data set and run internal CV to evaluate the model passed
X_test, y_test: this test data set for best model estimated.
nCV: Number of cross validation to run

Returns : modal_stats: a summary of best model

def evaluate_reg_model_performance(model_name,params,clf,score,X_train,y_train,X_test,y_test,nCV=10,n_jobs=1):
    # We prepare the grid search object
    # and custom scorer
    mape_scorer = make_scorer(score_func=mape, greater_is_better=False)
    scoring = {'RMSE': 'neg_root_mean_squared_error',
               'MAE': 'neg_mean_absolute_error',
               'MAPE': mape_scorer,
               'R2': 'r2'}
    
    grid = gridcv(clf, params, cv=nCV, scoring=scoring, n_jobs=n_jobs, refit=score, return_train_score=True)
    grid.fit(X_train, y_train)
    model_stat = pd.DataFrame()
    model_stat['model_name'] = [str(model_name)]
    print("Best parameters set found:")
    print(grid.best_params_)
    res = grid.cv_results_
    #pp = pprint.PrettyPrinter(indent=1)
    #pp.pprint(res)
    
    grid_scr = pd.DataFrame()
    grid_scr['params'] = res['params']
    grid_scr['RMSE'] = -res['mean_test_RMSE']    
    grid_scr['MAPE'] = -res['mean_test_MAPE']
    grid_scr['MAE'] = -res['mean_test_MAE']
    grid_scr['R2'] = res['mean_fit_time']

    grid_scr = pd.DataFrame(grid_scr)
    print('\nMean score summary of each gridsearch estimator executed')
    #display(Markdown(grid_scr.to_markdown()))    
    
    x = np.arange(len(grid_scr['params'])).astype(int)
    
    plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 6))

    plt.subplot(221)

    plt.ylabel('RMSE')
    #plt.xlabel('Parameter')

    plt.grid(color='grey', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.3)

    plt.bar(x, grid_scr['MAPE'])
    plt.ylabel('MAPE')
    #plt.xlabel('Parameter')
    plt.title('MAPE mean scores (nCV=%i)'%nCV)
    plt.grid(color='grey', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.3)

    plt.ylabel('MAE')
    plt.xlabel('Parameter')
    plt.title('MAE mean scores (nCV=%i)'%nCV)
    plt.grid(color='grey', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.3)
    
    plt.subplot(224)
    plt.bar(x, grid_scr['R2'])
    plt.ylabel('R2')
    plt.xlabel('Parameter')
    plt.title('R2 mean scores (nCV=%i)'%nCV)
    plt.grid(color='grey', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.3)
    
    plt.subplots_adjust(left=0.125, right=0.8, wspace=0.3, hspace=0.4)
    plt.show()    
    
    print(nCV, 'fold cross validation average scores of the best Estimator found by GridSearchCV\n')
    e = EvaluateRegressionEstimator(grid.best_estimator_, X_train, y_train, nCV)
    model_stat['model_name']
    model_stat['RMSE'] = grid_scr['RMSE']
    model_stat['MAPE'] = grid_scr['MAPE']
    model_stat['MAE'] = grid_scr['MAE']
    #model_stat['R2'] = grid_scr['R2']
    model_stat['time_refit'] = [grid.refit_time_]
    #display(Markdown(e.to_markdown()))
    #prediction
    
    if model_name in ['Linear Reg', 'Lasso Reg', 'Ridge Reg', 'Linear Reg_LDA', 'Lasso Reg_LDA', 'Ridge Reg_LDA']:
        plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 4))

        plt.show()
    else:
        grid.fit(X_train, y_train)
        yhat = grid.predict(X_test)
        plot_kde_y_yhat(y_test, yhat)
    
    yhat_df = pd.DataFrame(yhat)
    yhat_df = yhat_df.rename({0: model_name}, axis='columns')    
    
    return (model_stat, yhat_df)

KMeans Model¶

In this subsection, we will use KMeans techniques to build models. This technique is used widely in academia as well as in industry. KMeans techniques is easy to implement. In addition, it is also computationally very efficient. However, the clustering result can be bad or slow convergence if the initial centroids are chosen poorly. A smarter way of placing the initial cluster centroids in our lab is to use KMeans ++ which leads to better and more consistent results than the classical KMeans.

We now use the elbow method to find the optimal number of clusters. One of the main challenges in unsupervised learning is that we do not know the definitive answer. Based on the within-cluster SSE, we can use a graphical tool, elbow method, to estimate the optimal number of cluster $k$.

Clustering Evaluation¶

Next we use Silhouette Coefficient to do the clustering evaluation.

Silhouette refers to a method of interpretation and validation of consistency within clusters of data. The technique provides a succinct graphical representation of how well each object has been classified.

The silhouette value is a measure of how similar an object is to its own cluster (cohesion) compared to other clusters (separation). The silhouette ranges from 1 to +1, where a high value indicates that the object is well matched to its own cluster and poorly matched to neighboring clusters. If most objects have a high value, then the clustering configuration is appropriate. If many points have a low or negative value, then the clustering configuration may have too many or too few clusters.

The silhouette can be calculated with any distance metric, such as the Euclidean distance or the Manhattan distance.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silhouette

Gaussian Mixture Model¶

It is a probabilistic model for representing normally distributed subpopulations within an overall population. The technique has some advantages over KMeans techniques. It can handle even very oblong clusters. In addition, this algorithm is for soft clustering whereas the KMeans algorithm is for hard clustering.

In [47]:
import itertools
from scipy import linalg
import matplotlib as mpl
from sklearn import mixture

X = X_players_attack_scaled

lowest_bic = np.infty
bic = []
n_components_range = range(2, 9)
cv_types = ['spherical', 'diag', 'full']
for cv_type in cv_types:
    for n_components in n_components_range:
        # Fit a mixture of Gaussians with EM
        gmm = mixture.GaussianMixture(n_components=n_components, covariance_type=cv_type)
        _ = gmm.fit(X)
        bic.append(gmm.bic(X))
        if bic[-1] < lowest_bic:
            lowest_bic = bic[-1]
            best_gmm = gmm

# this code has been manipulated from the source available on sklearn's website documentation
# Plot the winner
plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
splot = plt.subplot(1,1,1)
Y_ = clf.predict(X)
for i, (mean, covar, color) in enumerate(zip(clf.means_, clf.covariances_,
                                             color_iter)):
    if len(covar.shape)<2:
        tmp = np.zeros((2,2))
        np.fill_diagonal(tmp,covar)
        covar = tmp
    elif covar.shape[0] != covar.shape[1]:
        covar = np.diag(covar)
        
    v, w = linalg.eigh(covar)
    if not np.any(Y_ == i):
        continue
    plt.scatter(X[Y_ == i, 0], X[Y_ == i, 1], .8, color=color)

    # Plot an ellipse to show the Gaussian component
    angle = np.arctan2(w[0][1], w[0][0])
    angle = 180 * angle / np.pi  # convert to degrees
    v *= 4
    ell = mpl.patches.Ellipse(mean, v[0], v[1], 180 + angle, color=color)
    ell.set_clip_box(splot.bbox)
    ell.set_alpha(.5)
    splot.add_artist(ell)

Spectral Clustering¶

In spectral clustering, the data points are treated as nodes of a graph. The method has become one of the most popular modern clustering algorithms. It uses information from the eigenvalues (spectrum) of special matrices (Affinity matrix, degree matrix, Laplacian matrix) derived from the graph or the data set.

(1) affinity = 'nearest_neighbors'¶

In [50]:
from sklearn.cluster import SpectralClustering
nclust = 3

# If a string, this may be one of nearest_neighbors, precomputed, rbf 
#  or one of the kernels supported by sklearn.metrics.pairwise_kernels
spc = SpectralClustering(n_clusters=nclust, affinity = 'nearest_neighbors')
labels = spc.fit_predict(X)

plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
plt.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=labels,cmap=plt.cm.rainbow, s=5, linewidths=0)

Based on the results above, we see that regression model types dominate the MAE results, and in each type of the model, we see little influence from the clustering. MAE scores are not always better for non clustering models and processing time is not always reduced for clustering models. There is no evidence that our assumption of the players can be clustered into different groups from the attacking features. However, since the clustering technique reduces the number of features we fit to the models. If the dataset is large, it can potentially reduce the processing time. In addition, we can potentially further reduce the processing time by clustering the other skillsets, e.g. mental, defending, movement and power features as we did for the attacking features.

Below is a summary of our clustering models with MAE score.

In [59]:
df_clustersummary.reset_index(drop = True)
Out[59]:
model_name BestCluster Param MAE
0 KMeans 3 3 clusters 4600.36
1 AgglomerativeClustering 3 link=complete, 3 clusters 4586.09
2 DBScan 3 minpoint=6, eps=.125 4568.05

For KMeans algorithm, there is an elbow at $k=3$. Then $k=3$ is the good choice based on elbow plot. Any lower value would be dramatic while any higher value would not help much. Another method that we used is silhouette score. This is the mean silhouette coefficient over the instances. In addition, with the silhouette diagram, we get more informative visualization. By the elbow plot, the silhouette diagram and MAE score, we arrive to choose $k=3$ for KMeans algorithm.

For DBSCAN algorithm, by using MAE score, the best instance's neigborhood is 0.125 and a core instance has at least 6 instances in its 0.125-neighborhood (including itself). The core instances are located in dense regions. This algorithm considers clusters as continuous regions of high density and the best number of clusters is 3.

For Agglomerative clustering algorithm, still using MAE score to evaluate models, the best number of clusters is 3 with complete linkage (the maximum distances between all observations of the two sets).

Since we were unable to get a MAE score on other clustering algoritms we did not include them in the table above, but the analysis of them are documented in the section above the algorithms in the notebook.

8. Deployment¶

Our goal of this lab is to use clustering to evaluate the model performance, MAE scores, of our wage prediction models. We did achieve our goal but not significantly. However, we discover using the clustering technique, we can potentially reduce our models processing time significantly.

Soccer clubs will be interested in our analyses. The Random Forest model with clustered features provide estimate of soccer players salary predictions. Clubs can offer salary when acquiring players base on the predictions. Also, the predictions can be a good reference when negotiating salary.

When a club is considering to trade players, we can deploy our models. For trading players, we can select players who the estimate salary are in the range of the budget. When there is a player the club wants to acquire, depending on how much desire the club wants to player, club can take the estimate salary as a reference. If the club thinks the player will fit well, it may offer salary that is higher than the estimate salary from our model. Also, when acquiring younger and newer players, the estimate salary can be a good reference because our model is driven by players' skills. We should collect the players' contract information so we can find out which players can be traded. Also, we can scrub players related news data so we can better understand players desires or preference.

The model need to be updated before trading windows or when club has a plan to trade a player. We can also potentially use the same strategy for other sport clubs, like football, volleyball, basketball, etc.

9. Exceptional Work¶

We will vizualize the attacking features clusters (that we got using KMeans against the two PCA components derived from the original attacking features). PCA is an unsupervised linear transformation technique for dimensionality reduction that is a useful technique when we have a large number of correlated features in the dataset. It allows us to summarize the information with a smaller number of collectively representative variables. This basically provides a better visualization of the clusters.
